Package: epimetrics
Title: Diagnostic Test Performance Metrics
Version: 0.0.1
Authors@R: 
    person("Nick", "Christofidis", , "nicolaos.christofidis@gmail.com", role = c("aut", "cre"),
           comment = c(ORCID = "0000-0002-9743-7342"))
Description: Easy estimation of diagnostic test performance using
    established epidemiological metrics. All metrics are accompanied with
    confidence intervals using the wilson-score and other methods to
    capture the experimental uncertainty, or can be easily simulated. All
    metrics accept either theoretical estimates of sensitivity,
    specificity and prevalence, or data related to a 2x2 confusion matrix.
    Parikh R, et al. (2008). Understanding and using sensitivity,
    specificity and predictive values. <doi:10.4103/0301-4738.37595>.
    Shan G (2015) Improved Confidence Intervals for the Youden Index.
    <doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0127272>. Bender R. (2001).  Calculating
    confidence intervals for the number needed to treat.  Control Clin
    Trials. <doi:10.1016/s0197-2456(00)00134-3>. Sakthivel Sivam, S. M.
    Everything or Nothing-A Better Confidence Intervals for Binomial
    Proportion in Clinical Trial Data Analysis.  Sakthivel Sivam,
    Quartesian LLC, Princeton, New Jersey Subbiah Meenakshisundaram, L. N
    Government College, Ponneri, India 2016 (2014).
    <https://www.lexjansen.com/pharmasug/2016/SP/PharmaSUG-2016-SP08.pdf>.
    Balayla J. (2020). Prevalence threshold and the geometry of screening
    curves.  <doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0240215>.  Kantele A et al. (2022).
    Scent dogs in detection of COVID-19: triple-blinded randomised trial
    and operational real-life screening in airport setting. BMJ Glob
    Health. <doi:10.1136/bmjgh-2021-008024>.  Daly, Leslie E (1998).
    Confidence Limits Made Easy: Interval Estimation Using a Substitution
    Method.  <doi:10.1093/oxfordjournals.aje.a009523>.
